</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4ABD561AD4CE2A42846F5250288E2535" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="52DB0A87351D6341DC56580FA88AE459" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EA41104963E0C421776A05EFAD1325A6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The heavily spinulose surstylus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F809A280F934DC049256CFBA4014D" authorityName="Lonsdale" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Agromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agromyza echinalis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="echinalis">
<emphasis id="D434C0812BE9BF42A1ABC894D7D374EC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agromyza echinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the primary defining feature that distinguishes it from other species with an enlarged first flagellomere. As in 
<taxonomicName id="0AF66C4C8C691DEFB542D97B26CDC881" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="A." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="A. tacita" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tacita">
<emphasis id="CD304BAE717E13BAA616D47117A83831" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. tacita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation id="7F6F9C02A710754C81B54A7C6C991DBB" captionStart="Figures 225–235" captionStartId="F35" captionText="Figures 225 - 235. 225 Agromyza tacita Spencer, wing 226, 227 A. tacita, external genitalia (New Hampshire male) 226 left lateral 227 ventral 228 - 231 A. tacita, genitalia (Plummers Island male) 228 external genitalia, ventral 229 phallus, ventral 230 phallus, left lateral 231 hypandrium and postgonite, ventral 232 - 235 A. echinalis Lonsdale, sp. nov., male holotype genitalia 232 external genitalia, ventral 233 external genitalia, left lateral 234 phallus, ventral 235 phallus, left lateral." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1051.64603.figures225-235" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/572134" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">226-228</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="17C4765BB85DECB7975B4358BE94764A" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="A." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="A. hockingi" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="hockingi">
<emphasis id="BBBF00893E996FA5E81A6556B9BCED10" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. hockingi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Colorado, Texas, Utah; 
<bibRefCitation id="A6C36F67F104B0772D0509848600612E" author="Spencer, KA" journalOrPublisher="Agriculture Handbook" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 478" publicationUrl="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" refId="B261" refString="Spencer, KA, Steyskal, GC, 1986b. Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. U.S.D.A. Agriculture Handbook 638: 1 - 478, https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" title="Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. U. S. D. A." url="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" volume="638" year="1986 b">Spencer and Steyskal 1986b</bibRefCitation>
: figs 411-413), the surstylus is triangular and clearly visible laterally, but these other two species have a slightly darker and more rounded surstylus with a maximum of five stout spines.
</paragraph>
